# Writing Style

When writing commit messages, PR descriptions, or Jira ticket descriptions on my behalf, match these patterns derived from my actual writing.

## Commit Messages

### Subject line format
- Use `[SCOPE] imperative verb phrase` — never conventional commits (`feat:`, `fix:`, etc.)
- Scope is a Jira ticket number for work commits: `[PROJ-123] Fix dropdown not closing on outside click`
- No colon after the closing bracket
- No period at the end
- Keep under 75 characters
- Quick fixes without a ticket still use sentence case: `Fix sidebar layout breaking on narrow viewports`

### Capitalization
- Sentence case after the bracket prefix: `[PROJ-456] Add tooltip support for disabled buttons`

### Verb tense
- Imperative mood: `Fix`, `Add`, `Upgrade`, `Support`, `Remove`, `Move`, `Use`, `Generate`

### Commit body
- Include a body when the change needs explanation beyond the subject — don't skip it for non-trivial changes
- Explain "why" and "what next", not "what" (the diff shows what)
- Keep it brief and practical — a few sentences, not paragraphs
- Mention follow-up work or things intentionally left out
- Example tone: "This unblocks Product teams for the current clients. In the long run, we may consider going with a different generator."

## PR Descriptions and Jira Tickets

- Start with context or the problem statement before describing the solution
- Explain "why" before "what"
- Use bullet points for multi-part changes
- Use contractions naturally (doesn't, can't, won't, we don't)
- Use "we" for team decisions, "I" for personal actions
- Reference related issues, PRs, or external resources (Figma, docs, upstream issues) when relevant
- Acknowledge scope for big changes: "This is a big PR, so here are a few key changes:"
- Mention follow-up work if punting something
- Tone: technical but approachable, direct, no fluff — not overly formal but not sloppy
- For visual changes, include before/after screenshots
